00:45:38.959 --> 00:45:47.840
But if you were to do a selection process, you know, obviously, it's somebody you feel that is

00:45:47.840 --> 00:45:53.520
a little bit, you know, more pivotal in an organization who can point you to the right

00:45:53.520 --> 00:46:00.560
resources and, you know, obviously, preferably, you know, a couple of levels above you so that,

00:46:00.560 --> 00:46:06.719
you know, it's somebody who's been through the rungs and knows what it takes to get up there.

00:46:08.399 --> 00:46:13.199
But actually not, I mean, it's not necessary, right? Like, it can be just somebody that you

00:46:13.199 --> 00:46:20.159
admire, and it could be a peer that you feel that you can really learn from and who sees you and

00:46:20.159 --> 00:46:27.040
wants to help you. So it's really about selecting somebody who you think's got your back at the end

00:46:27.040 --> 00:46:33.120
of the day, right? So the reason why I say initially, like, it's better if it's a skip-level

00:46:33.120 --> 00:46:40.080
person, because that person actually has the authority to bring you up with them, right? But

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:45.520
even if it's not that person, it's just somebody who's got your back, somebody who can see your

00:46:45.520 --> 00:46:52.159
good qualities and so is able to bring it out in you. That's who I would select.

